observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to reconcile the noted variance in the PPE accounts in the Statement of Financial Position against the Notes to the Financial Statements totaling ₱67,582,653.26, revise accordingly, and submit to the Audit Team the revised financial statements;
instruct the members of the Inventory Committee, who agreed to submit a written explanation on the rendering of the RPCPPE despite the non-conduct of physical count, and ensure that all PPE be completely counted near every year-end prior to the submission of the report to the Audit Team;
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to submit to the Audit Team the general ledgers of all PPE accounts as of December 31, 2024 for further evaluation;
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to ensure that PPE additions are properly recorded in the General Journal upon delivery or completion in compliance with Section 122 of the Manual;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant, who agreed to maintain PPELCs and Property Cards per type of property and complete with the necessary information as provided by each template. Ensure that all Property Numbers are unique for every type of property or asset, and that all PPE additions are easily identifiable to either a new or an existing PPE item; and
instruct the members of the Inventory Committee, who agreed to immediately initiate steps towards the carrying out of the one-time cleansing of PPE in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to:
submit a written explanation on the above-cited deficiencies, including other supporting documents or evidences, for further evaluation;
conduct reconciliation on the variances noted in Appendix H of ₱3,931,633.46 to ascertain completeness of depreciable items in the CY 2024 Lapsing Schedule;
conduct reconciliation on the variances noted in Appendix I of ₱2,811,397.29 and ₱80,605,112.01, and make the necessary revisions among the financial statements and/or the CY 2024 Lapsing Schedule;
conduct reconciliation on the variances noted in Depreciation Expenses accounts totaling ₱16,874,518.91 and ₱18.00 and make the necessary revisions among the financial statements and/or the CY 2024 Lapsing Schedule;
submit to the Audit Team the general ledgers of all depreciation expenses and accumulated depreciation accounts as of December 31, 2024 for further evaluation;
revise the format for the Lapsing Schedule, recompute the depreciation expenses for CY 2024 and accumulated depreciation balances as of January 1, 2024 and 2025, and make JEVs to reflect the accurate balances, taking into consideration the following:
ensure that depreciation commences on the date of delivery, in case of equipment, and on the date of project completion, in case of infrastructure assets, and in accordance with PAG for IPSAS 17;
ensure that the Lapsing Schedule presents depreciation expenses on a monthly basis and be provided with separate columns every month for depreciation expenses, disposals, adjustments, and carrying amount, among others;
ensure that road components are disaggregated and depreciated separately, and that the road lot component is not subjected to depreciation pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008;
ensure that salvage values for the Road Networks account not be provided with salvage values; and
identify the net book value of all PPE items replaced by subsequent rehabilitation projects and prepare JEVs to derecognize such in the books.

We recommended that Management:
submit a written explanation on the noted deficiencies for further evaluation;
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to revise the CY 2024 Notes to the Financial Statements to properly present the required disclosure on local roads in the format as prescribed in Annex B of the Circular.
instruct the Inventory Committee, who agreed to conduct a complete physical count of all road networks under their jurisdiction and render the Report on the Physical Count of LRN in the format as prescribed in Annex C of the Circular;
instruct the Municipal Engineer, who agreed to revisit the detailed costs relating to all local road networks, render a summary report presenting the segregated cost of each road component such as road lot, pavement, drainage and slope protection structures, and other miscellaneous structures, and immediately furnish such report to the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer, who agreed to expedite the preparation and/or maintenance of the Report on LRN and LRN Ledger Cards for each local road in the formats as prescribed in Annex A and E of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to expedite the preparation and maintenance of the LRN Ledger Cards for each local road in the format as prescribed in Annex D of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to:
create special accounts for the Operation of Badian Birthing Center and solid waste compromise fees pursuant to Municipal Ordinance No. 07-2017 and Municipal Ordinance No. 01-2005;
ensure that revenues and expenditures for all LEEs, including the Operation of Badian Birthing Center and solid waste management compromise fees, be separately estimated in the annual budget starting with the CY 2026 Annual Budget;
coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer and ensure that all operating expenses attributable to the operation of LEEs be properly charged within their respective appropriation line items;
ensure that all assets, liabilities, income and expenses for each LEE, including the Operation of Badian Birthing Center and solid waste management compromise fees, be separately accounted for, prepared with complete sets of books of accounts, general and subsidiary ledgers, and separate financial statements; and
revise and submit to the Audit Team the CY 2024 financial statements taking into consideration the disclosures on segment information as required in IPSAS 18 and COA Circular No. 2023-007.

We recommended that Management:
initiate steps towards the augmentation of the CY 2025 budget line items used as bases in the computation of the CY 2025 allowable CF to the “Peace and Order Program” special purpose appropriation line item;
instruct the Local Finance Committee, who agreed to ensure compliance with Sections 4.1.3 and 5.1.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 during budget preparation starting with the CY 2026 annual budget, with the end in view of ensuring compliance with the basis in the computation of the allowable CF;
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to ensure that all CF cash advances are properly debited to the Advances to Special Disbursing Officer account pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009;
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to prepare a JEV to record the liquidation of the CY 2024 fourth quarter CF cash advance in the CY 2024 books of accounts, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to prepare a JEV to reverse JEV No. 100-2025-01-0294 dated January 16, 2025, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to:
coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain independently the WOABSLC and WOABSPC in the formats as prescribed in Annex 8 and 38, respectively, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be disclosed. Ensure also that the WOABSLC and WOABSPC be reconciled on a regular basis;
submit a revised CY 2024 financial statements to correct Note 15 of the Notes to the Financial Statements to properly disclose the Loss on Initial Recognition of Biological Assets of ₱50,000.00 instead of Loss on Sale of Assets;
coordinate with the Municipal Agriculturist to determine the fair value less costs to sell of all breeding stocks as of December 31, 2024, including the offsprings, and submit a report to the Municipal Accountant for proper adjustment in the books;
prepare a JEV to record the year-end valuation of the Breeding Stocks account at fair value less cost to sell and submit the revised CY 2024 financial statements for further evaluation; and
coordinate with the Municipal Agriculturist and ensure to execute animal dispersal contracts with all recipients concerned, detailing the responsibilities of the Municipality and the recipients, among other necessary terms and conditions.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to:
prepare a JEV to reclassify the unliquidated CF cash advance of the former municipal mayor of ₱1,600,390.00, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
send demand letters requiring the former municipal mayor to immediately render full liquidation of his unliquidated cash advance of ₱87,682.00, otherwise, implement the applicable remedy such as initiate the filing of appropriate administrative and criminal proceedings against them;
trace records and documents, as far as practicable, to determine the nature of the transactions on balance of ₱9,080.50 and prepare JEVs, if necessary, to correct the Advances to Officers and Employees account;
prepare a JEV to reclassify the established cash shortage by the former municipal treasurer totaling ₱320,196.14, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
initiate steps towards the claim and recovery of receivables against either the estate or the heirs of the deceased former municipal treasurer for receivables totaling ₱320,196.14.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
submit a written explanation on the noted deficiencies;
submit to the Audit Team the lacking documents for further evaluation;
confer with the LMP regarding the issuance of official receipts without an ATP to the BIR; and
require the Municipal Accountant to make an adjusting journal entry on the CY 2024 transactions totaling ₱150,000.00 to properly record the financial assistance using the proposed adjusting journal entries below:

We recommended that Management:
instruct the LDRRMC, who agreed and confer with the SB to immediately craft and approve the revised CY 2025 LDRRMFIP, if necessary, taking into consideration the actual amount of appropriation of the CY 2025 current year LDRRMF and the Trust Liabilities – DRRMF balance as of January 1, 2025, with the end in view of ensuring that the revised LDRRMFIP reflects the actual available funds/ appropriations on LDRRMF for the year;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer, who agreed to:
immediately stop the practice of transferring an equivalent of 10 per cent of the NTA to the two LDRRMF bank accounts and ensure that actual fund transfers are only done practically towards the end of the year pursuant to Item 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
initiate steps, in coordination with the SB, towards the proper closure of the GF-LDRRMF bank account; and
coordinate with the Municipal Accountant, to determine whether the December 31, 2024 Cash in Bank balance of the TF-LDRRMF bank account match with the December 31, 2024 balance of the Trust Liabilities – DRRMF account and conduct reconciliation thereof, if necessary, to ensure over- or underfunding.

We recommended that Management:
instruct the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Treasurer, who agreed to:
identify all completed infrastructure projects as of date and determine their dates of completion, supposed defects liability period, and supposed date of final acceptance;
classify them according to building type (Types 1 to 5) and identify whether these are Permanent Structures, Semi-Permanent Structures, or Other Structures; and
immediately initiate steps towards the proper issuance Certificates of Final Acceptance by the Municipal Mayor on: (i) Permanent Structures, for those aged 15 years or below; (ii) Semi-Permanent Structures, for those aged 5 years or below; and (iii) Other Structures, for those aged two years or below;
prepare and submit to the Audit Team the status of the infrastructure assets as of date, including any details on any history of repairs, rehabilitations and renovations for further evaluation;
immediately issue Certificates of Final Acceptance one year after project completion;
demand from contractors the extension of validity period or, if already expired, the posting of another surety bonds for performance and warranty securities, taking into consideration the following:
for infrastructure projects still within the defect liability period, ensure that the coverage of the performance securities is until the last day of the defects liability period;
for infrastructure projects still within the warranty period, ensure that the coverage of the warranty securities is one year after the date of the Certificate of Final Acceptance;
ensure that the warranty securities do not contain any provision that would extinguish their liability against Structural Defects/Failures in accordance with the warranty period as prescribed in Section 62.2.3.2 of the IRR;
establish internal guidelines in the management of infrastructure projects, taking inspiration to DPWH DO No. 166, series of 2024, among other DPWH issuances. Ensure that controls are in place and working effectively to ascertain that the validity period for performance and warranty securities are sufficient cover the periods as prescribed in the IRR; and
submit to the Audit Team a written justification on the noted deficiencies, including copies of all of the above-cited documents, for further evaluation.

We recommended and Management agreed to initiate steps towards the revision of the Plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality, with emphasis on the following:
filling-in of vacancies in the Plantilla, especially the Assistant Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Agriculturist positions;
hiring JO workers only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160;
creation of the required divisions in the Municipal Treasury Office, such Cash Division, Revenue Division, Administrative Section, IT Unit, and Supplies and Property Division/Unit;
creation and filling-in Revenue Collector positions for the purpose of performing collection functions, with the end in view of eliminating or lessening the hiring of JO workers for the purpose;
matching of position titles and actual responsibilities of certain personnel in the MTO in accordance with the revised 2017 ORAOHRA;
creation and filling-in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the Municipal Assessor’s Office in compliance with RA No. 7160 and the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations; and
creation and filling-in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the MDRRMO in compliance with RA No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1.

We recommended and Management, through the GFPS, agreed to:
submit to the Audit Team a written explanation on the noted deficient GAD budget totaling ₱7,320,082.48 for further evaluation, and ensure that the CY 2026 GPB is at least five percent (5%) of the total Annual Budget. Also, initiate steps so that the CY 2025 GPB is compliant with the minimum as provided in PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended;
revise the CY 2024 GAD AR, taking into consideration the form as prescribed in Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended;
submit to the Audit Team proof of submission of the CY 2024 GAD AR to the Province of Cebu and the DILG in compliance with the JMC and the Full Disclosure Policy; otherwise, submit a written explanation on the non-compliance of such and immediately initiate steps towards compliance thereof;
submit to the Audit Team a written explanation, including supporting documents, on the non- or partial implementation of each of the GAD Activities totaling ₱6,550,800.00 and ₱1,087,070.00, respectively; and
submit to the Audit Team a written explanation, including supporting documents, on the noted excess actual expenditures on burial and medicine assistance of ₱134,010.00.

We recommended and the:
Inventory Committee and/or the personnel assigned in inventory taking agreed to diligently conduct the physical count of PPE items,  provide a reliable RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format of NGAS Manual and submit the same to the Audit Team not later than January 31;
Municipal Treasurer agreed to diligently prepare and provide complete Property Cards in the prescribed format of NGAS Manual;
Municipal Accountant agreed to trace and reconcile the discrepancies of balances between the books of accounts against the RPCPPE, Ledger Cards and Lapsing Schedule; and
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer agreed to facilitate the periodic reconciliation of their respective reports/records and make necessary adjustments, if any.

We reiterated our recommendation and the:
Inventory Committee agreed to submit the RPCI and thereafter, regularly submit the report not later than July 31 and January 31 each year;
Municipal Treasurer/GSO-Designate agreed to prepare the Stock Cards following the prescribed format in the Manual and submit the same to the Audit Team;
Municipal Accountant agreed to prepare the Supplies Ledger Cards following the prescribed format in the Manual and submit the same to the Audit Team; and
Accounting and Treasury offices agreed to reconcile their respective records of the inventory accounts.

We recommended and the Municipal Engineer agreed to submit the following:
Justification why the contract time of the project was not determined in accordance with Annex A of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
Evaluation Report and its supporting documents establishing the need for time extension including the computation showing in sufficient detail how the number of days of extension was determined;
Approved PERT/CPM Network Diagram reflecting the effect of the subject time extensions on the original contract time; and
Explanation on the approval of time extension in excess of 100% of the original construction period.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to ensure:
Submission of the Consolidated Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and Consolidated Monthly Report of Official Travels in CY 2023 to the Audit Team to facilitate the validation of the reasonableness of fuel consumption of the Municipality;
Completeness of the supporting documents for every transaction to ensure that all disbursements are properly documented;
That Driver’s Trip Tickets are serially numbered and properly accomplished indicating all the necessary information therein for every trip undertaken; and
That every Trip are supported with Driver’s Trip Tickets.

